‘ The next winner ’ continues Pausanias ‘ was Philam- mon, and next to him Philammon’s son Thamyris. Orpheus, however, gave himself such airs because of the Mysteries that he would not enter for the prize, and Musaeus, who laid himself out to copy Orpheus, followed his example.’ This seems to mean that Orpheus and Musaeus, as belonging to the Eleusinian Mysteries of Demeter, could not reasonably be supposed to have competed in a Hymn to Apollo.
